title: Neds Corner - Plants
description: Area incorporating the Neds Corner property (Trust for Nature) and the adjoining Murray River frontage.

items.title: Minuria integerrima
items.content_text: A single flowering plant.

items.title: Senecio platylepis
items.content_text: Annual herb less than 40cm tall. Only this single flowering plant observed. Previous weeks have seen very good rains.

items.title: Xanthium strumarium spp. agg.
items.content_text: Growing along edge of Murray River.

items.title: Goodenia fascicularis
items.content_text: Not especially silky, but all other characters point to Goodenia fascicularis, which has previously been observed in this area.

items.title: Sarcozona praecox
items.content_text: Differentiate from co-existing Noon-flower by triangular cross-section of leaves, paler leaves that are often red-tinged, and flowers that do not ascend above leaves (in Noon-flower flowers sit above leaves).

items.title: Osteocarpum salsuginosum
items.content_text:
Growing near edge of Alectryon oleifolius tree. Not commonly encountered here.
Fruit required to confidently differentiate from very similar Osteocarpum acropterum.

items.title: Silene apetala var. apetala
items.content_text: Exotic annual herb, growing here less than 20cm tall near the base of Alectryon oleifolius subsp. canescens.

items.title: Rhodanthe stricta
items.content_text: Single plant observed at this location, within 25 metres of Murray River bank. Rare plant across this landscape.

items.title: Fumaria bastardii
items.content_text: Only a single, small patch of plants observed growing within 20 metres of Murray River bank.

items.title: Hyalosperma glutinosum subsp. glutinosum
items.content_text: Plants are about twice the size of the more widespread H. semisterile.

items.title: Rhodanthe stricta
items.content_text: New location for this plant at Neds. This species is only known at Neds and one other location in Victoria.

items.title: Rhodanthe stricta
items.content_text: New location for this plant at Neds. This species is only known at Neds and one other location in Victoria.

items.title: Brachyscome melanocarpa
items.content_text: 10 or so plants on the edge of a very lush depression. This is the second known population of this  plant in Victoria. Peter Barnes led us to this population which he has known about for many years. ID confirmed by Neville Walsh.

items.title: Hypoxis glabella var. glabella
items.content_text: New species record for Neds Corner. ID confirmed by Neville Walsh. Photos show some features required for determination at species level (eg. two non-sheathing bracteoles towards the base of the flower stem - see 3rd photo). This taxon has recently changed name from Hypoxis glabella.

items.title: Brachyscome melanocarpa
items.content_text: Location is where the species was discovered in Victoria in 2011.

items.title: Brachyscome melanocarpa
items.content_text: Location is where this species was discovered for Victoria in 2011, until now the only population known in Victoria. The plant in the first two pics was in dry soil at the outer edge of a gilgai and exposed to full sun. This made this plant a little depauperate. This plant also had the best flower at this location. Plants were found both sides of the track in the numerous small depressions/gilgais, always at the outer edge of the depression.

items.title: Plagiobothrys plurisepalus, Plagiobothrys spp.
items.content_text: Developing fruit.

items.title: Centipeda crateriformis subsp. compacta
items.content_text: In a dried up creek bed growing alongside C. nidiformis.

items.title: Centipeda nidiformis
items.content_text: In a dried up creek bed growing alongside C. crateriformis subsp. compacta. Species feature is its hairiness, which is rare among Centipeda.

items.title: Lepidium phlebopetalum
items.content_text: Plants spreading by stolons - see pic 2. Fruit are the round structures. Leaves linearish.

items.title: Sclerolaena decurrens
items.content_text: Hairy (pic1) and glabrescent (pic2) forms growing together. ID by Nathan Wong.

items.title: Myosurus australis
items.content_text: In a dried up creek bed.

items.title: Maireana ciliata
items.content_text: Unusual to see a Maireana so small and with prostrate, lanky habit.

items.title: Brachyscome dentata
items.content_text: Lobed seed (2nd pic) is a key feature of this species, along with the leaf tips being lobed.

items.title: Frankenia serpyllifolia
items.content_text: Only a few plants spotted at this location, pink- and white-flowered plants.

items.title: Elachanthus glaber
items.content_text: Small herb in large numbers but over just about 20m x 10m at this spot. One plant of the smaller Elachanthus pusillus also found at this spot.

items.title: Olearia pimeleoides
items.content_text: On roadside when entering Neds.

items.title: Lawrencia glomerata
items.content_text: A few dozen plants on a saltpan.

items.title: Elachanthus pusillus
items.content_text: Red-tipped and fringed bracts are a key feature of this species. Single individual of this tiny herb found among large numbers of Elachanthus glaber covering an area of just about 20m x 10m. Elachanthus pusillus is considerably smaller than E. glaber and has red-tipped and fringed apex to bracts plus bristly-hairy leaves. E. glaber has none of these features.

items.title: Maireana aphylla
items.content_text: Just one plant at this location.

items.title: Rostraria pumila
items.content_text: Not sure of ID.

items.title: Schismus barbatus
items.content_text: Not sure of ID.

items.title: Hordeum spp.
items.content_text: The presence of auricles on the leaves suggests H. glaucum or leporinum and discounts marinum and hystrix as possibilities (maybe) but it could be other species too.

items.title: Chthonocephalus pseudevax
items.content_text: A really tiny plant - just an inch or so across and virtually no height. Blends in with similar coloured and shaped lichen at this location. Found by Nathan Wong.

items.title: Osteocarpum acropterum var. deminutum
items.content_text: Fruit can be seen in-situ in the first pic. ID by Nathan Wong.

items.title: Bulbine semibarbata
items.content_text: Note the hair tufts at the base of stamens on the longer three filaments only. Bulbine alata has hair tufts at the base of each stamen.

items.title: Pogona vitticeps, Sonchus asper subsp. asper
items.content_text: Central Bearded Dragon feeding on the flowers of Sonchus asper (Sow Thistle).

items.title: Nicotiana glauca
items.content_text: Standing beside plants: Peter Barnes (right), Russell Best (front left), James Booth (left hidden).

items.title: Gypsophila tubulosa

items.title: Sarcozona praecox
items.content_text: Leaves triangularish in cross-section.

items.title: Medicago truncatula
items.content_text: Just visible is the laciniate stipule, leaf apex obviously dentate. Leaf upper surface hairy.

items.title: Goodenia pusilliflora
items.content_text: Tiny flower.

items.title: Thysanotus baueri
items.content_text: In bud. Leaves wither at time of flowering.

items.title: Zygophyllum simile
items.content_text: White flowers, 4 petals, 8 stamens.

items.title: Myoporum platycarpum subsp. platycarpum
items.content_text: Mature tree branches flexuose and petals shorter than floral tube for this subspecies.

items.title: Lepidium papillosum
items.content_text: 2nd pic shows unusual hairs at full res.

items.title: Angianthus spp.

items.title: Chrysocephalum spp.
items.content_text: A surprising find at this location. Looks like C. sp. 2 but I note that C. apiculatum has recently been recorded nearby (but on the Murray riverside).

items.title: Sisymbrium spp.
items.content_text: Possibly S. irio (possibly S. orientale).

items.title: Harmsiodoxa blennodioides
items.content_text: Mostly white, rarely pink flowers (2nd pic).

items.title: Minuria denticulata

items.title: Minuria cunninghamii

items.title: Convolvulus remotus
items.content_text: About 100m of white flowered plants on roadside only (no plants at all away from roadside), probably a result of the grader. Some were twining through other plants but this one had nothing to climb on. It was GPSed but I uploaded unGPSed pics.
